Asynchronous I/O (Non‑Blocking)

The program does not wait for the I/O operation to finish.

Instead, it delegates the task to the system (via Libuv’s event loop/thread pool).

Meanwhile, the main thread continues executing other code.

## When the I/O task completes, a callback/promise is triggered to handle the result.

Event Loop
The event loop is the core mechanism in Node.js (via Libuv) that continuously checks for tasks/events.
✅ Event Loop → Helps Node.js perform asynchronous tasks on the same single thread.
It keeps checking the task queue, picks up callbacks when async operations finish, and executes them without blocking the main thread.

✅ Thread Pool → Handles heavy or blocking tasks (like file system operations, DNS lookups, crypto).
These tasks are offloaded to background worker threads managed by Libuv, so the main event loop stays free to keep processing other requests.
